        Chart Review 08/11/24

        Screw Elon Musk and everything he stands for.

        Sorry, I know I shouldn't be plugging my political opinions in anybody's faces after the past couple weeks, and whatever farcicalities were going on in the Album Chart comment sections should also be wavered away as an argument no one needed to initiate, but it's kinda difficult to keep quiet after the USA elected Donald Trump for another 4 years of wacky hijinks. Not that I have anything against the most famous tan-man in the world, but it feels a bit suspect that a guy with a humorous mugshot is leading America to try and fix their problems or whatever. Either way, the moral of the story here? Never hire any famous musicians to carry your campaigns. Because now people are gonna look at BRAT (Collins word of the year by the way) in a bad light after Kamala Harris completely shafted it.

        Obviously, the British chart hasn't been affected by this at all, but you really wish it did because THERE'S NOTHING NEW AGAIN. Apart from the No.1 slot, because Gigi Perez has the defensive capabilities of that Armenian team Chelsea played against last night, as she trades her chart-topping slot with everybody's favourite female singer-songwriter Gracie Abrams. Everbody's favourite. Ignore the fact that all of her hits seem to be a DIY spreadsheet of musical copyright (Close To You is reminiscent of Julia Michaels, I Love You, I'm Sorry sounds like Taylor Swift, us. actaully has Taylor Swift), and with That's So True casually giving her a No.1 single for the first time, you can totally appreciate just how easy it is to do bits in the charts these days. Just tour with someone famous and you're set for life.

        Apart from that though there's little to talk about, the 2 new entries being the latest Weeknd song to creep out of the speakers and bore me to tears, Sao Paulo having Brazilian superstar Anitta to vaguely spice up the action (either that or the video put me off my drink), and one of the Tyler, The Creator album tracks being replaced by another one that doesn't sound as amazing. Good for Lola Young that she gets to terrorise the chart for the first time, but did Like Him really have to replace my personal favourite off CHROMAKOPIA? And over on the album chart it's a glorious day for supporters of The Cure as their first album since Comet was on the high street powers past all opposition to make the music scene as gloomy and brooding as ever. Even if I prefer Friday I'm In Love to anything off Songs Of A Lost World.
